data.content:
Yes — MSTest v3.6+ supports **strongly-typed data** via tuples, eliminating the `object[]` casting:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**What changed:**
- `IEnumerable<object[]>` → `IEnumerable<(string, bool)>` — compile-time type checking
- Array literals `["x", true]` → tuple literals `("x", true)`

This gives you IDE autocompletion, refactoring support, and compile errors if types don't match. Requires **MSTest 3.6+** (`MSTest.TestFramework` NuGet package).
